What is JAR stand for ?

    Java Archive

What is compile time and run time?

    Compile Time:
        The time for the source code to compile into machine code in order to become and executable program.
    Runtime:
        The time for the program/application already compiled running.

What is heap?

    -The runtime data area from which memory for all class instances and arrays is allocated.
    -Created on virtual machine start-up.
    -Its' storage for objects is reclaimed by an automatic storage management system, a garbage collector; objects are never
      explicitly de-allocated.

How java manage it's memory?

    The java objects reside in an area called the heap.
    The heap is created when the JVM starts up and may increase or decrease in size while the application runs. When the heap
    becomes full, garbage is collected. During the garbage collection objects that are no longer used are cleared, thus making
    space for new objects.

What is the difference between String, StringBuffer and StringBuilder?

    String:
        -It is an immutable object;
    StringBuffer/StringBuilder:
        -It is an mutable object;
        StringBuffer:
            -It is synchronized.
        StringBuilder:
            -It is not synchronized.

What is Singleton class?

    The use of Singleton class is to keep only one instance of a class at any time and its purpose to control object creation
    by keeping private constructor.

What is Serialization and Deserialization?

    Serialization:
         A process of converting an object into a sequence of bytes which can be persisted to a disk or database or can be sent
         through streams.
    Deserialization:
        It is the reverse process of creating object from sequence of bytes.

Which one will take more memory, an int or Integer?

    Integer

Why is String Immutable in Java?

     Because Java uses the concept of string literally. For example, if there were 5 reference variables all refers to one String
     object and if one reference variable changes the value of the object, then it will be affected to all the reference variables.

What is constructor chaining in Java?

    It is the process of calling one constructor from another constructor. It is either calling another constructor using the keyword
    "this()" with the specific number of parameter in the same class; or using the keyword "super()" from another class, known as parent
    class when one class extends another class.

The difference between Serial and Parallel Garbage Collector?

    Parallel Garbage Collector uses multiple thread for garbage collection operation than Serial Garbage Collector.

What is JIT stands for?

    JIT, Just In Time.

Explain Java Heap space and Garbage collection?

    Heap in Java generally located at bottom of address space and move upwards. Whenever create an object using new operator or by any
    another means the object is allocated memory from Heap. And when object dies or garbage collected, memory goes back to Heap space
    in Java. And JVM provides the mechanism of Garbage collection to reclaim heap space from objects which are eligible for Garbage
    collection.

Can you guarantee the garbage collection process?

    In Java, Yes. The programmer does not need to care for all those objects which are no longer in use as Garbage collector destroys
    them.

What is the difference between stack and heap in Java?

    Stack memory is used to store local variables and function call as Heap memory is used to store objects in Java.
    In the computer's RAM, Stack is used for static memory allocation and Heap is used for dynamic memory allocation.